&lt;p>Pointers are one of the most powerful but complex topics in C++. They allow you to work with memory directly, which makes the code more flexible and efficient. Let&amp;rsquo;s figure out how they work!&lt;/p>
&lt;h3 id="-what-is-a-pointer">ðŸ”¹ What is a pointer?&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>A pointer is a variable that stores the &lt;strong>address of another variable&lt;/strong> in memory. He announces himself like this:&lt;br>
``cpp
int* ptr; // ptr is a pointer to the int type&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-gdscript3" data-lang="gdscript3">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="c1">### ðŸ”¹ How do I get the address of a variable? &lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="n">Using&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">the&lt;/span> &lt;span class="s1">&amp;#39;&amp;amp;` operator: &lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="err">```&lt;/span>&lt;span class="n">cpp&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="ne">int&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">num&lt;/span> &lt;span class="o">=&lt;/span> &lt;span class="mi">10&lt;/span>&lt;span class="p">;&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="ne">int&lt;/span>&lt;span class="o">*&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">ptr&lt;/span> &lt;span class="o">=&lt;/span> &lt;span class="o">&amp;amp;&lt;/span>&lt;span class="n">num&lt;/span>&lt;span class="p">;&lt;/span> &lt;span class="o">//&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">ptr&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">now&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">stores&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">the&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">address&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">of&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">num&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;h3 id="-pointer-dereference">ðŸ”¹ Pointer dereference&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>To get the value at the address, use the &lt;code>*&lt;/code> operator.:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-cpp" data-lang="cpp">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="n">cout&lt;/span> &lt;span class="o">&amp;lt;&amp;lt;&lt;/span> &lt;span class="o">*&lt;/span>&lt;span class="n">ptr&lt;/span>&lt;span class="p">;&lt;/span> &lt;span class="c1">// Outputs 10 (the value of num)
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="c1">&lt;/span>&lt;span class="err">``&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="cp">### ðŸ”¹ Dynamic memory
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="cp">&lt;/span>&lt;span class="n">Pointers&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">are&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">often&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">used&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">to&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">work&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">with&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">dynamic&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">memory&lt;/span>&lt;span class="p">.&lt;/span>&lt;span class="o">:&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="err">``&lt;/span>&lt;span class="n">cpp&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="kt">int&lt;/span>&lt;span class="o">*&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">arr&lt;/span> &lt;span class="o">=&lt;/span> &lt;span class="k">new&lt;/span> &lt;span class="kt">int&lt;/span>&lt;span class="p">[&lt;/span>&lt;span class="mi">10&lt;/span>&lt;span class="p">];&lt;/span> &lt;span class="c1">// Allocated memory for the
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="c1">&lt;/span>&lt;span class="k">delete&lt;/span>&lt;span class="p">[]&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">arr&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">array&lt;/span>&lt;span class="p">;&lt;/span> &lt;span class="c1">// Don&amp;#39;t forget to release!
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;h3 id="-nullptr-instead-of-null">ðŸ”¹ nullptr instead of NULL&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>In modern C++, it is better to use &lt;code>nullptr&lt;/code> for empty pointers.:&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" class="chroma">&lt;code class="language-cpp" data-lang="cpp">&lt;span class="line">&lt;span class="cl">&lt;span class="kt">int&lt;/span>&lt;span class="o">*&lt;/span> &lt;span class="n">ptr&lt;/span> &lt;span class="o">=&lt;/span> &lt;span class="k">nullptr&lt;/span>&lt;span class="p">;&lt;/span> &lt;span class="c1">// The pointer does not refer to anything
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;h3 id="-why-is-this-necessary">ðŸ”¹ Why is this necessary?&lt;/h3>
&lt;p>Pointers are used for:&lt;/p>
&lt;ul>
&lt;li>Works with dynamic structures (arrays, lists).&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Transfer big data to functions without copying.&lt;/li>
&lt;li>Polymorphism (through pointers to base classes).&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;p>&lt;strong>, Advice:&lt;/strong> Always check the pointers for &lt;code>nullptr&lt;/code> before using!&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>